ions of revolutionary transformation but also the dense entanglements among those in the top echelon of the party. Wang discusses the causes for failure of China’s socialist revolution and raises fundamental questions about male dominance in social movements that aim to pursue social justice and equality. This is the first book engendering the PRC high politics and has important theoretical and methodological implications for scholars and students working in gender studies as well as China studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx1949-1976xChina. 0aFeminismxPolitical aspectszChinaxHistoryy1949-1976. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectsxHistoryx1949-1976xChina. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszChinaxHistoryy1949-1976. 0aSocialism and motion picturesxHistoryx1949-1976xChinaxChina. 0aSocialism and motion pictureszChinaxHistoryy1949-1976. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxChina. 0aWomenzChinaxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066754740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965867?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965867423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965867/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles